Twitter displays the Chinese character for “fall/autumn” or “harvest” (秋) on top. Moon Cake was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Lobster
description: A lobster, a large crustacean with a prominent tail and pincers. Depicted as a reddish-orange lobster (as cooked) from above, with a long body and tail, short, tentacle-like eyes, and ten legs, the top of which are very large pincers.Often used to represent lobster as food as well as in connection to the US state of Maine.In its release year of 2018, Emojipedia’s original sample image was criticized as anatomically incorrect but was shortly after resolved. That year, the transgender community embraced the lobster as a symbol for their efforts for Transgender Flag emoji.Samsung, WhatsApp, and Facebook’s lobsters are depicted at an angle. Lobster was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Cupcake
description: An individual cupcake in a liner topped with a swirl of frosting and sprinkles. The style of cupcake widely varies across platforms. The cake may be sponge or chocolate, the frosting pink or white, and the sprinkles rainbow or red. Cupcake was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Compass
description: A magnetic compass, as used for navigation. Generally depicted in a silver or gold case with a compass rose and a red-tipped needle. Commonly used for various content concerning traveling and exploring as well as metaphorical compasses (e.g., moral compass).Facebook’s markings include the initials of the four cardinal directions, north, south, east, and west. Not to be confused with various clock or timepiece emojis. Compass was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Brick
description: A red brick or bricks. Depicted in a loose stack, a single object with holes, or as built into wall, as of a house, school, or other structure.Commonly used for various content concerning building and construction. May also be used for figurative bricks, e.g., slang brick, “extremely cold (weather).” Brick was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Skateboard
description: A skateboard emoji, usually showing the board from the top.Twitter's design shows the under-side of the board, as did a previous Microsoft design.Emojipedia's sample image was modelled after Tony Hawk's skateboard. Skateboard was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Luggage
description: A suitcase or bag, as used for traveling. Most platforms depict gray or blue rolling luggage with an extended handle. Commonly used for various content concerning traveling or taking trips, whether for business or leisure.Apple’s design features an old-fashioned, leather, trunk-styled case with graphic luggage labels/stickers, not to be confused with 💼 Briefcase or 👜 Handbag. Google and Facebook also include such stickers.May be stored in a 🛅 Coin Locker or inspected at 🛃 Customs. Luggage was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Firecracker
description: A firecracker, as lit on Chinese New Year, New Year's Eve, or Independence Day. Depicted as a red tube with a burning fuse, sometimes lined with gold rings at its top and base.Often used with 🎆 Fireworks and 🎇 Sparkler for various celebrations and holidays. Also applied to figurative senses of fire, e.g., slang hot, on fire (“excellent”).While it may resemble a stick of dynamite on some platforms, several vendor designs, such as Google and Twitter's, suggest the emoji is modeled after traditional Chinese firecrackers, as are strung together and lit on such occasions as Chinese New Year. Firecracker was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Red Envelope
description: A red envelope, as gifted with money on Chinese New Year or on other joyous occasions, such as weddings, in Chinese and some other Asian cultures around the world.Depicted as a red, vertical envelope with a gold design, typically featuring the Chinese character 福 (fú, “good fortune, luck, happiness"). Google’s design previously featured the character upside down, indicating “good luck arrives.”Often used to celebrate and wish good fortune on Chinese New Year (Lunar New Year, Spring Festival). Also used to represent gifts, celebration, Chinese culture, and the color red more generally. Red Envelope was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 under the name “Red Gift Envelope” and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Softball
description: A softball, which is differentiated from a baseball by size (it is larger, though hard to tell in emoji form) and color (yellow, not white). Softball was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Flying Disc
description: A flying disc, more commonly known as a frisbee. Used in the sport of Ultimate or disc golf. Flying Disc was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Lacrosse
description: Lacrosse was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 under the name “Lacrosse Stick and Ball” and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Nazar Amulet
description: A nazar, an eye-shaped amulet believed to protect against the evil eye, especially in Turkish culture. Depicted as a rich blue, circular bead with a black dot in the center ringed with white and light blue, resembling an eye.Commonly used to represent eyes, various senses of looking, various senses of charms, envy and jealousy, and Turkey and Turkish culture. Also used for its blue color more generally.WhatsApp and Facebook's designs include a small hole, as for threading the amulet on a string or chain. Nazar Amulet was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Puzzle Piece
description: Puzzle Piece was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 under the name “Jigsaw Puzzle Piece” and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Teddy Bear
description: A classic teddy bear, as snuggled by a child when going to sleep.Depicted as a brown, stuffed toy bear, shown seated with its arms to the sides, hind paw pads facing forward, and a friendly smile on its face. Google, WhatsApp, and Twitter's designs include a ribbon around the neck, while Facebook's is wearing a bow tie.Commonly used to convey something or someone is cute or cuddly (e.g., teddy bear as a term of endearment) as well as other warm, loving sentiments (e.g., get well soon). May also be used for various content concerning toys and children more generally.Not to be confused with 🐻 Bear Face, though their applications may overlap. Teddy Bear was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Thread
description: A spool of thread, as used for sewing. Thread color varies across platforms, though often depicted in red or blue and on a wooden spool. Sometimes shown with an end unraveling.Commonly used for various content concerning sewing, knitting, arts and crafts, clothing and fashion, and metaphorical threads (e.g., a discussion thread online).WhatsApp and Microsoft's designs includes a needle. Thread was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 under the name “Spool of Thread” and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Yarn
description: A ball of yarn, as used to knit a scarf. Color varies across platforms, but often depicted in green, blue, or magenta and shown with an end unraveling. Sometimes depicted with a pair of knitting needles stuck in the ball.Commonly used for various content concerning knitting and needlework (e.g., sewing, crocheting), clothing and fashion, arts and crafts, cold weather, and cats. Yarn was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 under the name “Ball of Yarn” and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Goggles
description: Clear safety goggles. When this emoji was approved in 2018 it was implied to be safety goggles rather than swimming goggles. A year later 🤿 Diving Mask, which is similar in design but used to represent swimming goggles rather than safety goggles, was approved. Goggles was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Lab Coat
description: A white coat worn in a science laboratory. Lab Coat was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Hiking Boot
description: A style of boot commonly worn on long walks or for hiking. Generally distinct from other footwear-related emojis by the considerable grip on the sole of the shoe. Hiking Boot was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Flat Shoe
description: A flat shoe, in a style generally worn by women. More practical than a high-heeled shoe. Flat Shoe was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Abacus
description: An abacus, an ancient tool used to count and calculate by moving beads. Depicted as a wooden frame with four or more rows or columns of variously positioned and colored beads.Used for various content concerning mathematics and science (education) as well as calculations, counting, and numbers more generally.Designs from Apple and Facebook resemble a Chinese abacus (suanpan), as did a previous Microsoft design. By one reckoning, Apple’s red-beaded design displays the number 108 and Emojipedia's, 12,031,981. Abacus was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Receipt
description: A white paper receipt, as proof of payment, and shown flat or curled. May be used for other financial documents (e.g., invoice, tax form). May also be used for the slang receipts, or "evidence” or “confirmation” of some feat or controversy.Some vendors feature easter eggs. Apple’s design, for instance, displays the date of July 17 (World Emoji Day); items referencing its 1997–2002 Crazy Ones/Think Different ad campaign (misfits, square pegs, round holes); and a balance $0.00. Receipt was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Toolbox
description: A red box for holding and transporting tools, such as a hammer and wrench. Generally depicted as latched shut with silver hardware and a black handle.Commonly used for literal or metaphorical tools, toolkits, and building.WhatsApp's design includes a hammer in front. Google’s design was previously shown as open with two wrenches and a pair of pliers. Toolbox was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Magnet
description: A horseshoe magnet, as used to pick up iron. Depicted at various angles in red with silver-tipped poles.Commonly used for various content concerning literal and figurative magnetism and attraction. May also be used in various science-related contexts more generally.Twitter’s design features two electric bolts coming from its poles. WhatsApp’s horseshoe is half blue, denoting an opposite magnetic pole. Magnet was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Test Tube
description: A test tube, as used to conduct chemical experiments in a laboratory. Depicted as a clear cylinder, open at one end and containing a green liquid. Positioned at a 45° angle.May be used for various content concerning chemistry and science more generally. May also represent other liquids, such as potions or medicines, as well metaphorical laboratories and experiments.Some platforms include volume markings or display the liquid as bubbling. WhatsApp’s design features a blue liquid. Test Tube was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Petri Dish
description: A petri dish, as used to culture microbes. Depicted as a clear, shallow cylinder with a red, blue, or green growth medium, such as agar, with splotches of variously colored cells, like bacteria.May be used for various content concerning biology and science more generally. May also be used to represent germs and other microorganisms.Samsung’s design features a lid, while Google’s design previously featured a dropper. Petri Dish was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: DNA
description: The double helix of DNA, the genetic blueprint for life. Color and orientation vary across platforms, but positioned at a 45° angle and in multiple, bright colors to represent the molecule’s spiraling, ladder-like structure.May be used for various content concerning biology, genetics, and science more generally. May also be used for various content concerning literal or figurative life and evolution. DNA was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 under the name “DNA Double Helix” and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Lotion Bottle
description: A bottle of lotion for the skin, such as moisturizer or sunscreen (sunblock). May be used for other hygienic liquids, including shampoo and body wash, as well as beauty products.Appearance varies across platforms, but commonly depicted in white and gold colors. Some platforms, like Apple and Twitter, feature a bottle with a pump while others show a cylinder with a cap. Lotion Bottle was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Safety Pin
description: A silver safety pin or clip, as used to fasten fabric. Generally shown clasped at a 45° angle, with its spring at the lower left.May be used for various content concerning arts, crafts, and sewing. Not to be confused with 📎 Paperclip. Safety Pin was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Broom
description: A traditional broom, as used for sweeping—or ridden by a witch. Shown at a 45° angle, with a wooden handle and yellow bristles at the lower left.Commonly used for various content concerning cleaning, brushing, and figurative sweeps (e.g., in sports or awards). Not to be confused with 🖌️ Paintbrush. Broom was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Basket
description: A basket, as used for storing or carrying such things as food or clothes. Appearance widely varies across platforms but generally depicted as woven from wicker with one or more handles. Commonly used to represent doing laundry or having a picnic.Apple and WhatsApp’s designs, featuring a white cloth, suggest a bread or picnic basket. Samsung’s design displays green fabric, as knitted from yarn.Microsoft’s design previously suggested a laundry basket by holding a blue garment or cloth.Not to be confused with 🗑️ Wastebasket. Basket was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Roll of Paper
description: A roll of paper, as toilet paper (toilet tissue). May also be a roll of kitchen/paper towels. Depicted at various angles, with a sheet unfurling.Commonly used for toilet paper but may also be used for various content concerning toilets, going to the bathroom, bathrooms, cleaning, or paper more generally. Roll of Paper was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Soap
description: A bar of soap, as used in the shower, bath or for hand washing. Generally shown with lathered bubbles. Depicted in various colors, often pink, and at different angles.Commonly used for various content concerning bathing, washing, and cleaning. May be used to represent the opposite of dirt or being dirty. Recommended for use to prevent the spread of COVID-19. Soap was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 under the name “Bar of Soap” and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Sponge
description: A peanut-shaped sponge, as used for cleaning or bathing. Generally depicted in yellow and at different angles across platforms. Commonly used for various content concerning bathing, washing, and cleaning. Sponge was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Fire Extinguisher
description: A fire extinguisher, as used to put out small fires. Depicted as a red tank with a black hose and pressure gauge. Most platforms include an image of a flame on a white label.Commonly used for various content concerning fire safety, emergencies, and literal and figurative fires. Fire Extinguisher was approved as part of Unicode 11.0 in 2018 and added to Emoji 11.0 in 2018.

name: Smiling Face with Tear
description: A yellow face with open eyes, a thin closed-mouth smile, and a single tear falling from one of its eyes. Can be used to express a wide range of emotions and expressions including gratitude, tender happiness, an attempt to look happy when actually sad, or smiling through pain. Can also be a response to something that is bittersweet.This emoji and 🙂 Slightly Smiling Face have a similar smile, and 😢 Crying Face and 😿 Crying Cat have a similar lone tear. Not to be confused with 😂 Face with Tears of Joy, which has a wide toothy grin and tears coming from both eyes. Smiling Face with Tear was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Disguised Face
description: A yellow face with big glasses, a large nose, thick eyebrows, and a mustache. Used to represent someone in disguise.The features of this particular disguised face are taken from the “Groucho Mask” or “Groucho Glasses,” designed in the likeness of the caricature played by Julius Henry Marx in the Marx Brothers' films. These comedic films were popular in the 1930s and ‘40s, and the mask has been a mainstay of joke shops since as early as the 1940s.Other emoji faces in disguise include 🦸 Superhero and 🦹 Supervillain. Disguised Face was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Pinched Fingers
description: An emoji showing the fingers held together in a vertical orientation, often referred to as the Italian hand gesture ma che vuoi, sometimes called the "finger purse." In Italy this gesture tends to be used in disagreement, frustration, or disbelief and can mean “What do you want?” or “What are you saying?” Outside Italy anyone performing a caricature of an Italian person, regardless of context or tone, might use this gesture.Pinched Fingers has a variety of other culturally specific uses. In Israeli culture it can mean “hold on,” “relax,” or “be patient.” The K-Pop star Yuri uses it as a signature gesture to represent a dumpling and a general warm sentiment. It can also be used to represent the act of fisting.Not to be confused with 🤏 Pinching Hand, which has overlapping senses. Both are used to represent precision when someone is making a sharp point with accompanying speech. Pinched Fingers was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Anatomical Heart
description: A red anatomical heart, shown with blue or purple veins on some platforms.Sometimes used interchangeably with ❤️ Red Heart. Anatomical Heart was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Lungs
description: Pink anatomical lungs and trachea, shown with bronchial tubes on some platforms. Used in medical contexts to talk about lung health. Sometimes used in reference to taking deep breaths, hyperventilating, or breathing in general. Also used in the context of smoking or vaping. Lungs was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Ninja
description: A person dressed as a ninja with a black hood, a mask covering the lower half of their face, and the hilt of a knife or sword emerging from behind their shoulder.The now-discontinued Microsoft ZWJ sequence 🐱‍👤 Ninja Cat did not include the ninja emoji at all as it was developed several years before ninja was approved. It combined 🐱 Cat Face and 👤 Bust in Silhouette and was only available from Microsoft prior to the debut of the Fluent emoji set in November 2021. Ninja was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: People Hugging
description: Two people hugging, shown as faceless blue forms on most platforms. Details of each person are not distinct and thus no options are available to customize the gender or skin tone of either individual.Not to be confused with 🤗 Hugging Face, which is less clearly a representation of hugging and sometimes used as jazz hands or to express excitement. People Hugging was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Bison
description: A brown bison shown in full profile with horns, a beard, and woolly mane. Also called a buffalo in North America. Bison was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Mammoth
description: A brown wooly mammoth with large curved tusks. Can also be used to represent a mastodon. Mammoth was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Beaver
description: A brown beaver with buckteeth and a wide paddle-like tail. Can be used in the context of actual beavers, or metaphorically to evoke qualities of beavers like working hard, as in the expression beavering away. Commonly associated with Canada, as beavers are a national emblem of the country. May also be used in reference to the vagina, which is an informal sense of the word beaver. Beaver was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Dodo
description: A brown or gray dodo shown in full profile. Generally depicted with a curved yellow beak, small wings, a fluffy white tail, yellow or orange feet, and black talons.May be used to represent dodos or the concept of being extinct. Dodo was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Feather
description: A single feather slanted to one side. On most platforms it's light brown with a dark brown barred or striped pattern. Can be used to talk about feathers or birds, or to represent something that is lightweight, fluffy, or soft. Feather was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Seal
description: A gray seal with dark eyes and a dark nose. Most platforms feature a design with whiskers.Can be used to talk about seals, marine life, or cute animals in general. May also be used in phrases with 'sealed' as in sealed with a kiss, my lips are sealed, or signed, sealed, and delivered. Seal was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Beetle
description: A green or brown beetle shown with antennae and six legs. Can be used to talk about beetles, bugs, or insects in general.Not to be confused with 🐞 Lady Beetle, 🪳 Cockroach, 🐛 Bug, 🐜 Ant or other emoji representations of insects. Beetle was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Cockroach
description: A brown cockroach shown with antennae, six legs, and two sensory pads at its rear called cerci.Can be used to talk about cockroaches or insects in general. May also be used metaphorically as an insult to call a person a pest, an annoyance, or to suggest they are subhuman.    Cockroach was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Fly
description: A fly with a dark or iridescent green body, six legs, and two translucent wings. On most platforms, its eyes are red.Can be used to talk about the insect or flight in general. May also be used metaphorically as an adjective meaning "cool." Fly was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Worm
description: A pink or brown worm. Most platforms have more realistic designs, though Google and Samsung feature cartoony worms who are smiling sweetly.Can be used to talk about worms or disease spread by worms. Can also be used to refer to a deceitful person. May be used to in reference to the dance move 'the worm.' Worm was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Potted Plant
description: A leafy green plant in pot. Plant type varies by platform. Potted Plant was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Blueberries
description: A few ripe blueberries clustered together. Most platforms show three blueberries, and some show small green leaves coming out from behind the blueberries. Blueberries was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Olive
description: One, two, or three green olives, either pitted or sprouting from a branch. Some platforms show a solitary pitted green olive stuffed with a piece of a pimento pepper.Can be used to talk about olives or the color green.  Olive was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Bell Pepper
description: A perfectly ripe red or green bell pepper. Can be used to talk about bell peppers or food in general. Bell Pepper was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Flatbread
description: A round piece of flatbread with grill marks. Used to represent any type of flatbread, soft or crunchy.Can be used to talk about corn-based flatbreads popular in Central and South America like arepa, gordita, or pupusa. Can also be used in reference to other flatbreads including naan, lavash, matzah, and pita.Not to be confused with 🥙 Stuffed Flatbread. Flatbread was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Tamale
description: A single tamale wrapped in a corn husk. Tamale was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Fondue
description: A red fondue pot. Most platforms show cheese fondue with fondue forks sticking out of the pot. Fondue was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Teapot
description: A classic teapot with a wide bulbous body, a spout, a handle, and a lid. Can be used to talk about tea, tea time, or warm beverages in general.May also be used to talk about gossip as in the expression spill the tea. Teapot was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Bubble Tea
description: Bubble tea is a tea-based drink invented in Taiwan which typically contain tea, flavored milk, and sugar. Commonly served with tapioca pearls, also known as boba, in a plastic cup with a wide straw. Bubble Tea was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Rock
description: A large rock the size of a small rock. May be considered a boulder, a rock, a stone, a pebble, or a piece of dirt. The scale and meaning are context dependent.The color is gray or brownish gray. Rock was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Wood
description: One or two stumps of wood, cut so the rings are showing. Can be used to talk about wood or building materials. Also used in idioms with wood like knock on wood or out of the woods. Used to caption dic pics, often alongside the expression morning wood. Sometimes used in the context of games like Catan or Minecraft, where wood is a resource. Wood was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Hut
description: A round hut with a thatched roof. Used to talk about huts, cottages, yurts, or homes in general. Hut was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Pickup Truck
description: A red or turquoise pickup truck. Used to talk about trucks or modes of transportation in general. Pickup Truck was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Roller Skate
description: A single vibrantly colored roller skate. Colors and styles vary across platform. Roller Skate was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Magic Wand
description: A wand with sparkles (✨magic✨) coming out of its end. Most platforms show a classic magician-style magic wand that's black with white tips. WhatsApp shows a golden magic wand tipped with a star, similar to the wand that Glenda the Good Witch uses in the 1939 film The Wizard of Oz. Magic Wand was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Piñata
description: A colorful decorated container that comes in many shapes, a piñata is filled with candy or toys. Hit to break open for celebrations such as Cinco de Mayo, this is generally associated with Mexico.Displayed as a donkey on some platforms, and as a three-dimensional star with 6–9 points on others. Piñata was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 under the name “Pinata” and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Nesting Dolls
description: Nesting dolls, also called matryoshka dolls or Russian dolls, decorated with bright colors including red, yellow, blue, and green. All platforms depict the nesting dolls as open, revealing smaller dolls within the bases of larger dolls. Dolls are all decorated with women wearing headscarfs. Some platforms show a flower motif on the women's dresses or aprons. Nesting Dolls was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Sewing Needle
description: A threaded silver needle. Color of thread varies from platform to platform.Can be used to talk about crafts including embroidery, quilting, or sewing in general. Can also be used in medical contexts to talk about stitches.Used metaphorically at the beginning of a thread, or series of connected posts by one person, on social media. Sewing Needle was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Knot
description: Brightly colored rope forming a knot. Knot type varies across platform, with most designs showing a square knot, a figure eight knot, or a carrick bend. Samsung's design appears to be a carrick bend, but upon closer inspection, it is not correctly tied and would fall apart with a gentle tug. Used to talk about rope or knots in general. Sometimes used in the context of marriage alongside the idiom tying the knot. Also used in the kink community to talk about bondage. May be used as a stand-in for the word 'not' in emoji rebus puzzles. Knot was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Thong Sandal
description: A single flip flop or thong sandal. Often worn to the beach and/or in warm weather. Can be used to talk about sandals, the beach, or warm weather in general. Thong Sandal was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Military Helmet
description: A round military helmet with a chinstrap. All platforms depict a green helmet, with some designs featuring a green camouflage pattern. Military Helmet was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Accordion
description: A red accordion with a keyboard on one side, buttons on the other side, and bellows in the middle. Used to talk about accordion music or music in general. Also may be used in reference to things that expand and contract, or are folded like the bellows of an accordion. Accordion was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Long Drum
description: A long drum with a tall body and a cylindrical or hourglass shell. Can be used to represent various drums found around the world from Africa to the Caribbean to Latin America to Asia. Types of long drum include (but are not limited to) djembe, talking drum, conga, bongo, tumbadora, atabaque, and dhol.Can also be used to talk about drums, music, or beats in general. Long Drum was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Coin
description: A coin shown in silver or gold. Design varies by platform, with Google and Twitter showing a 🏛️ Classical Building and Samsung showing the number one, similar to their 🥇 1st Place Medal design.Apple’s coin has the text "The Crazy Ones," a reference to its 1997–2002 Crazy Ones/Think Different ad campaign and commonly used as placeholder text in Apple icons and emoji designs. Coin was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Boomerang
description: A wooden boomerang with bright colors on its tips. Google and Twitter's designs show motion lines to illustrate the path of a boomerang.Used literally to represent a boomerang. Also used to represent Aboriginal people or Australia in general. May be used to represent something that comes back or returns. Boomerang was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Carpentry Saw
description: A long silver saw with a wooden handle. Used to represent construction, carpentry, renovation, or tools in general. Carpentry Saw was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Screwdriver
description: A silver Phillips-head or slotted-head screwdriver with a colorful handle. Most platforms show a red handle, though Apple's design has a green handle. Used to represent construction, building, carpentry, renovation, or tools in general.Sometimes used in phrases with 'screw' in them like screw you or have a screw loose. Can also be used in sexual contexts due to the informal meaning of 'screw': "to have sex." Screwdriver was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Hook
description: A gold or silver hook. Can be used to represent literal hooks like the kinds you use to crochet or catch fish.Also use metaphorically to talk about boxing or punching, music (the catchy part of a song), or in phrases like hook me up, hook up, getting hooked (on something), or hook, line, and sinker.  Hook was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Ladder
description: A wooden ladder with four or five rungs.Used to represent ladders or the action of climbing. Also used metaphorically to represent systems through which you can climb, for example the corporate ladder or social ladder. Ladder was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Elevator
description: A symbol showing two or three people standing in a square with up and down arrows above them. Most platforms feature a simple blue and white design.Mostly used to talk about elevators. Also used metaphorically to talk about moving or leveling up or down. Elevator was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Mirror
description: A mirror with an ornate gold or silver frame. The shape and style of the mirror varies from platform to platform.Used to talk about mirrors, reflection, or self-reflection.  Mirror was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Window
description: A square or rectangular window with glass panes. Most platforms show a wooden frame with two or four panels.Used to talk about actual windows or metaphorical windows, which often represent opportunities, perspectives, or unique points of view.  Window was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Plunger
description: A toilet plunger with a wooden handle and red flange and cup.Used to talk about toilets and clogged pipes. Also used metaphorically to talk about a mess or something that's disgusting. Plunger was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Mouse Trap
description: A trap used to catch a mouse, rat, or other unwanted rodent. Metaphorically used in emoji form to suggest any kind of trap or entrapment.The style of trap shown on major platforms has a box held high with a single stick. A wedge of cheese is used to lure a mouse into the box, knocking the stick away and trapping — but not killing — the mouse.This is distinct from other traps which kill or injure upon capture. Mouse Trap was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Bucket
description: A blue or green bucket or pail. Used to talk about real or metaphorical buckets.May be used to talk about bucket lists, kicking the bucket, making baskets in basketball, an abundance of something (like rain or money), and many other contexts. Bucket was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Toothbrush
description: A brightly colored plastic toothbrush with white bristles.Used to talk about oral hygiene, daily routines, or something that is fresh and clean.  Toothbrush was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Headstone
description: A headstone or tombstone, used to mark graves. Appearance varies from platform to platform, with different shapes and inscriptions.Used to talk about death — literally, metaphorically, and metaphysically.Often paired with other death-related emoji like ⚰️ Coffin and ☠️ Skull and Crossbones. Headstone was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Placard
description: A sign on a post, commonly used to promote ideas, causes, or make announcements. Often used used in the context of politics to represent a lawn sign or a poster brought to a protest. Also seen in commercial advertising.Shown with indiscernible writing or not writing at all, this emoji is flexible in its use. WhatsApp shows a peace sign, which tilts the meaning away from commercial use. Placard was approved as part of Unicode 13.0 in 2020 and added to Emoji 13.0 in 2020.

name: Yawning Face
description: A yellow face with eyes closed and mouth wide open covered by a hand. Captured mid-yawn, this may represent having insufficient sleep, or to imply boredom with a person or topic.Not to be confused with 😪 Sleepy Face or 😴 Sleeping Face, which often convey actually being asleep, or 😫 Tired Face which is tired as in "fed up". Yawning Face was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Brown Heart
description: A brown heart, often used discuss topics related to racial identity 🧑🏽🧑🏾🧑🏿The least used of the nine colored hearts (❤️🧡💛💚💙💜🖤🤍🤎). Brown Heart was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: White Heart
description: A white heart emoji, used for love and affection. Also commonly used to discuss someone passing away.An alternative character known as White Heart Suit is also available, but not intended to have an emoji appearance. White Heart was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Pinching Hand
description: A hand with thumb and index finger in close proximity. Used to suggest that something is small, or to gesture a small amount. Has Pinching Hand was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Mechanical Arm
description: A mechanical or prosthetic arm. Mechanical Arm was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Mechanical Leg
description: A mechanical or prosthetic leg. Mechanical Leg was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Ear with Hearing Aid
description: An ear shown with a hearing aid, worn by a person with hearing loss. The style shown in Behind The Ear (BTE), but this can represent any form of hearing aid. Ear with Hearing Aid was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Deaf Person
description: A person gesturing with their index finger between ear and mouth, used as a deaf sign in American Sign Language (ASL) and a number of other global sign languages. See also 🦻 Ear With Hearing Aid. Deaf Person was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019. 🚩 Previously displayed a gendered appearance, now shown as gender neutral on most platforms.

name: Person Standing
description: A person standing upright. Commonly used to convey awkwardness, particularly on TikTok.Similar in appearance to 🚶 Person Walking, but shown facing forward and without any motion implied. Person Standing was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name “Standing Person” and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Person Kneeling
description: A person kneeling on both knees. May be used to represent someone in prayer, or a person resting on the floor. Person Kneeling was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name “Kneeling Person” and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019. 🚩 Previously displayed a gendered appearance, now shown as gender neutral on most platforms.

name: Orangutan
description: An orangutan, the orange-haired ape with long arms. Depicted facing forward, with a long broad face and sitting with its legs bent. Occasionally shown scratching its head. Color varies across platforms, ranging from orange to light brown.This emoji is considered racist in some contexts, particularly when used to disparage, insult, and abuse people with dark skin, especially Black people. Orangutan was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Guide Dog
description: A guide (or Seeing Eye) dog, trained to help lead a person who is blind or visually impaired. Generally depicted as a yellowish-brown Labrador Retriever on all fours facing left, equipped with a harness and handle. Many platforms additionally include a collar.Not to be confused with 🐕‍🦺 Service Dog, though their popular applications may overlap.Twitter implements the same dog as its 🐕 Dog. Samsung and Twitter’s guide dogs have green harnesses. Guide Dog was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Sloth
description: A sloth, the slow-moving, tree-dwelling mammal. Depicted as a light-brown sloth with a wide, whitish, masked face hanging from a tree branch, facing left or right. Generally shown as a three-toed sloth. Sloth was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Otter
description: An otter, the playful water mammal in the weasel family. Depicted as a light-brown otter on its back, with its forepaws held together and whiskered face to the left, generally with its long tail curled up.Apple’s otter is in water, holding a stone, as is Microsoft’s. Otter was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Skunk
description: A skunk, a bushy-tailed mammal that sprays a foul odor when threatened. Depicted in full profile on all fours facing left, with black hair and its distinctive white stripe running from its head down to a curled-up tail.Google’s original skunk design bore a humorously haughty air. Skunk was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Flamingo
description: A flamingo, a waterbird with pink feathers and long neck and legs. Depicted as a flamingo in full profile facing left, standing on one leg, usually with a long, black beak.May be used to represent summer fun or as a pink accent color. Flamingo was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Garlic
description: A single white or light brown bulb of garlic. Can be used to talk about cooking, eating, or vampire protection. Garlic was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Onion
description: A round yellow onion. Can be used to talk about cooking, eating, or crying. Sometimes used in metaphors about layers. Might also be used in computing contexts in reference to onion routing. Onion was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Waffle
description: A round or square Belgian waffle, baked to a golden brown. Most platforms depict this emoji topped with a pad of butter, and some include gooey syrup running down the sides. Waffle was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Falafel
description: Brown spheres depicting falafel, a food popular in Middle Eastern and North African cuisine, typically made of mashed chickpeas or fava beans. Most platforms include three or more falafel with one piece split open to reveal a green center. Can be used to talk about falafel and possibly other round brown food items like meatballs.On several platforms 🥙 Stuffed Flatbread appears to be filled with falafel, so for some users, these two emoji might be interchangeable. Falafel was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Butter
description: A pale yellow stick of butter. Can be used to talk about cooking or eating. Might also be used in idioms or to reference something that is smooth. Butter was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Oyster
description: Half of an opened oyster shell with gray, pink, or orange flesh inside. Many platforms also include a pearl in the shell. Oyster was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Beverage Box
description: Originally proposed as Juice, this emoji can be used to talk about juice or other liquids that come in boxes with straws. It can also be used metaphorically to talk about power, energy, respect, or an elusive quality that makes someone special. Beverage Box was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Mate
description: Mate is a caffeinated beverage popular in many South American countries. Green in color (from a key ingredient: the dried leaves of yerba mate) and consumed via a metal straw.This drink is commonly referred to as yerba mate in English, and sometimes spelled maté (to distinguish from a mate, as in friend). Mate was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name “Mate Drink” and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Ice
description: A blue cube of ice. Can be used to talk about ice or cold temperatures in general. This emoji can also be used metaphorically to talk about something that is cool or chill. Ice was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name “Ice Cube” and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Hindu Temple
description: A Hindu temple or mandir; a place of worship for followers of Hinduism. Depicted on most platforms as a red, orange, or golden building with a tall spire. Hindu Temple was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Manual Wheelchair
description: A manual wheelchair. Most platforms show a red and black or blue and black wheelchair. Distinct from ♿ Wheelchair Symbol, which is used as signage to indicate accessible facilities. See also 👩‍🦽Woman in Manual Wheelchair or 👨‍🦽Man in Manual Wheelchair.🦼 Motorized Wheelchair was approved at the same time as this emoji. Manual Wheelchair was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Motorized Wheelchair
description: A motorized wheelchair. Most platforms show a red and black or blue and black wheelchair. Distinct from ♿ Wheelchair Symbol which is used as signage to indicate accessible facilities. See also 👩‍🦼Woman in Motorized Wheelchair or 👨‍🦼Man in Motorized Wheelchair.🦽 Manual Wheelchair was approved at the same time as this emoji. Motorized Wheelchair was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Auto Rickshaw
description: An auto rickshaw, often referred to as a tuk tuk. This motorized version of a cycle rickshaw is used for transport in many regions of the world. Generally this emoji has three wheels and open sides without doors. Auto Rickshaw was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Parachute
description: An open parachute floating through the air with a human steering. Most platforms feature a ram-air design. Colors vary across platforms. Parachute was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Ringed Planet
description: A ringed planet that appears with various number of rings, tilt angles, and colors across platforms. This vaguely Saturn-like orb was proposed as a stand-alone planet emoji to represent all planets. Ringed Planet was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Diving Mask
description: A diving mask with a snorkel, used for scuba diving or other underwater activities. Colors vary across platforms.🥽 Goggles is similar in design, but used primarily to represent safety goggles rather than swimming goggles. Diving Mask was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Yo-Yo
description: A round yo-yo with its string coming out. It appears in various colors and designs across platforms, occasionally with a ⭐ Star on its side.WhatsApp's yo-yo design displays the company's logo. Yo-Yo was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Kite
description: A diamond-shaped kite with a tail. This emoji appears in various colors across platforms. Kite was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Safety Vest
description: An orange safety vest with reflective lines across the chest and over the shoulders.Used in the ZWJ sequence 🐕‍🦺 Service Dog, which was approved at the same time. A safety vest can also be seen in the designs of 👷 Construction Worker on multiple platforms. Safety Vest was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Sari
description: A brightly colored sari draped in different ways across platforms. Sometimes used to mean a dress in general.This emoji is sometimes used playfully in English to stand in for the word 'sorry.' Sari was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: One-Piece Swimsuit
description: A sporty one-piece swimsuit shown in a variety of colors and patterns across different platforms.Related emojis include 👙 Bikini, 🩳 Shorts, and 🩲 Briefs. One-Piece Swimsuit was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Briefs
description: Underwear or swim briefs. The swimming variety are often called 'Speedos' after the brand. This emoji is shown in different colors and styles across platforms. Some platforms depict this emoji as tighty whities with a visible fly, while others use a less specific design.Related emojis include 👙 Bikini, 🩳 Shorts, and 🩱 One-Piece Swimsuit. Briefs was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Shorts
description: Shorts or swimming trunks. This emoji is shown in different colors and styles across platforms. Most platforms depict this emoji in a casual sporty style.Related emojis include 👙 Bikini, 🩲 Briefs, and 🩱 One-Piece Swimsuit. Shorts was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Ballet Shoes
description: Shoes worn by ballet dancers for pointe work. Most platforms show a pair of pink shoes resting on their pointes. Sometimes used to represent dancing in general, rather than ballet specifically. Sometimes also used to represent the color pink. Ballet Shoes was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Banjo
description: A banjo with a round body and a long neck. Used to talk about banjos or music in general. Banjo was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Diya Lamp
description: A lamp made of brass or clay, displayed with a lit wick leading into oil or ghee.Commonly used in Hindu, Sikh, Jain and Zoroastrian religious festivals such as Diwali. Diya Lamp was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Axe
description: An axe with a wooden handle and a metal blade. On many platforms the blade is red, like a fire axe. Axe was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: White Cane
description: A white cane, used by some people who are blind or visually impaired. The cane has a black or gray handle with a wrist loop, a white middle section, and a red end with a white cap. This cane differs from a support cane and is sometimes called a probing cane.👩‍🦯 Woman With Probing Cane and 👨‍🦯 Man With Probing Cane are ZWJ sequences that use White Cane. White Cane was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name “Probing Cane” and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Drop of Blood
description: A red drop of blood. May be used to talk about bleeding, injury, blood donation, or menstruation. Drop of Blood was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Adhesive Bandage
Stethoscope
description: A stethoscope with a round resonator and two earpieces. Shown in black, blue, green, or red, depending on the platform. Stethoscope was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Chair
description: A simple wooden chair.Distinct from 💺 Seat, which is generally depicted as a fixed plane, train, or bus seat, as opposed to a chair which can be moved.May have sexual connotations (e.g., sit on my face). May also be used as a TikTok convention to signify laughter or approval or to create confusion for people not in the know. Chair was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Razor
description: A safety razor, depicted in various colors across platforms.Previously shown as a straight razor by Microsoft, WhatsApp, and JoyPixels. Razor was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Orange Circle
description: Orange Circle was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name “Large Orange Circle” and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Yellow Circle
description: Yellow Circle was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name “Large Yellow Circle” and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Green Circle
description: Green Circle was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name “Large Green Circle” and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Purple Circle
description: Purple Circle was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name “Large Purple Circle” and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Brown Circle
description: Brown Circle was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name “Large Brown Circle” and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Red Square
description: A square shown in the color red. May be used to represent anything red, including a red penalty card in football (soccer). Red Square was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name “Large Red Square” and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Orange Square
description: A square shown in the color of orange. May be used to represent anything orange. Orange Square was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name “Large Orange Square” and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Yellow Square
description: A square shown in the color yellow. May be used to represent anything yellow, including a yellow penalty card in football (soccer). Yellow Square was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name “Large Yellow Square” and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Green Square
description: A square shown in the color of green. May be used to represent anything green.May 2021: Sometimes shown in Twitter names in support of Taproot, a Bitcoin fork (potential feature change) that would allow additional privacy measures for transactions. Green Square was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name “Large Green Square” and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Blue Square
description: A square shown in the color of blue. May be used to represent anything blue. Blue Square was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 under the name “Large Blue Square” and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

name: Purple Square
